---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE_CONFIG } from '@/lib/siteConfig';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="William Zujkowski — security engineer, builder, homelab enthusiast.">
  <div class="prose">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm a Senior InfoSec Engineer at <a href="https://cloud.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Cloud.gov</a>,
      focused on cloud platform security, identity federation, and compliance automation.
      I design security controls that enable teams instead of blocking them — and spend
      too many nights in my homelab breaking things to understand how they work.
    </p>

    <p>
      Everything on this site reflects my own views, not those of my employer.
    </p>

    <h2>Background</h2>

    <p>
      My first computer was a Tandy 286 from Radio Shack — the floor model. I upgraded it to Windows 3.1
      with 30-something floppy disks. By the late 90s I had a Geocities site. By the early 2000s I was
      running self-hosted PHP forums on a PC under my bed with over 500 users.
    </p>

    <p>
      That turned into nearly a decade of fixing computers for small businesses in the Harrisburg, PA area,
      which led to infrastructure management, which led to security engineering. The pivot point: recovering
      a machine from an MBR virus for someone working on their thesis. Classic "I need help, here's pizza"
      situation. To this day, when a bad CVE drops, I grab pastries for the response team.
    </p>

    <h2>Career</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Cloud.gov</strong> (2023–present) — Cloud security architecture and federal compliance for a
      FedRAMP Moderate platform. NIST 800-53 Rev 4 → Rev 5 transition.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>NIH</strong> (2014–2023) — Moved through HPC site reliability, enterprise vulnerability
      management across 100,000+ assets and 27 Institutes, and security engineering for research infrastructure.
      Led the Log4j response. Got to burn in 8-way H100 nodes.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Independent consultant</strong> (2005–2014) — House calls to infrastructure management.
      Nearly a decade of learning how things break in the real world.
    </p>

    <h2>How I Think About Security</h2>

    <p>
      Security should enable work, not block it. The best controls are invisible — users never notice them
      because they just work. If developers can't deploy their code, they'll find a workaround. Make the
      secure path the easy path.
    </p>

    <p>
      Automation isn't about replacing people. It's about freeing them from clicking buttons so they can do
      interesting work. AI security is about governance, not just tech — the hard problems are the humans,
      policies, and processes around the models.
    </p>

    <h2>Outside Work</h2>

    <p>
      My homelab has grown from a single Raspberry Pi in 2015 to a Dell PowerEdge R910, a fleet of Pis,
      and way too many containers. I run my own SIEM, self-hosted password manager, and whatever else
      I'm experimenting with that week. I've burned out a GPU pushing local LLM inference too hard
      and taken down my home network for hours trying VLAN segmentation "just to see how it works."
    </p>

    <p>
      I'm deep into AI/LLM experimentation — not just using models, but running them locally, building
      multi-agent orchestration systems, and figuring out how to secure these things in production.
      See what I'm building on the <a href="/projects/">projects page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Connect</h2>

    <p>
      <a href={SITE_CONFIG.social.github} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a> ·
      <a href={SITE_CONFIG.social.linkedin} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">LinkedIn</a> ·
      <a href="/feed.xml">RSS</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
